                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
                <html:p>Now, we want to show that if any sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> has the property, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex> has it as well.
There are three possibilities:
<html:ol><html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, or</html:li>
<html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, or</html:li>
<html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ol></html:p>
                <html:p>We can think about these in turn:
<html:ol><html:li>if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, then since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> is a strong Kleene valuation, it must be that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, so since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> has the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> property, we know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, so since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t]]></fr:tex> is a Dunn-Belnap valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>;</html:li>
<html:li>if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, then by similar reasoning <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>; and</html:li>
<html:li>if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>, then by similar reasoning <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ol></html:p>
                <html:p>This shows that, no matter what <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A)]]></fr:tex> is, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t(\neg  A)]]></fr:tex> is related to it in the right way.
So as long as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> has the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> property, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex> has it as well; this shows that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg ]]></fr:tex> preserves the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> property.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
