      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td class="fade"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
  </html:tbody>
</html:table>
                <html:p>And now you can compare that to the strong Kleene table to see that these tables match on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, and that they use <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> in the same places as each other.
So <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\rightarrow ]]></fr:tex> too preserves the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> property.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>28</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/005R/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>005R</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/005R/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Other connectives">Other connectives</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>To conclude that every sentence has the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> property, we need to know that <html:em>every</html:em> connective, not just <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\rightarrow ]]></fr:tex>, preserves the property.
But here I'll just tell you: they do.</html:p>
                <html:p>You should know now, though, how you would go about discovering this; what you would be looking at about each connective in turn in order to detect whether that connective does or does not preserve the property.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>Since every connective preserves the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> property, and every atomic sentence has the property, we can conclude that every sentence has the property.
This lets us know that, given any strong Kleene valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>, we can generate a Dunn-Belnap valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t]]></fr:tex> that matches <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> on all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> values, and that uses <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> wherever <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> uses <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <html:p>Combining this with what we learned before, we now know that every strong Kleene valuation can be turned into a Dunn-Belnap valuation two <html:em>different</html:em> ways: we can treat <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> everywhere as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>, or we can treat it everywhere as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex>.
Again, put a pin in that for now.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
